---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What's the difference between a roof paint and a roof restoration in Hobart?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A roof paint is just the topcoat — clean, prime, coat. A roof restoration includes the structural work that sits underneath: re-bedding any loose ridge capping, re-pointing the entire ridge and hip line with flexible pointing compound, replacing broken or shattered tiles, and only then doing the wash-prime-coat sequence. On a Hobart tile roof — most often Wunderlich concrete or terracotta on 1950s-1980s housing stock — the bedding and pointing under the ridge caps are usually the actual problem. A paint job over failed pointing buys you two to three years of looking nice before water finds its way through the joints. A restoration buys you 10-15." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I tell if I need a restoration rather than just a paint?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Three checks. First, walk the perimeter and look up at the ridge line — if you can see any pointing cracked, missing or sitting proud of the cap, the ridge work is overdue and a topcoat alone won't fix it. Second, check for any displaced or broken tiles in the field; one obvious break usually means three or four less obvious ones. Third, get into the roof space on a wet day with a torch and look for any active drip or stain — a water mark on a rafter under the ridge line is a definitive restoration call. We do this as a 32-point inspection at quote stage and write up which path is appropriate for your roof." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does a 'paint your roof for $X' quote leave out in Hobart?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Almost always the bedding and pointing inspection, the broken-tile replacement allowance, and the workmanship warranty on the structural elements. A low-headline-price roof paint quote in Hobart typically covers a wash and a single colour topcoat sprayed on, with no allowance for the actual roof condition underneath. That's fine if the pointing is genuinely sound, but on a 30-40 year old tile roof in Glenorchy, Moonah or Lindisfarne it almost never is. Hobart's freeze-thaw cycle — overnight lows that push roof surface temperature below zero on clear winter nights — accelerates rigid-mortar pointing failure compared to mainland cities. Always check the quote line items." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What's the warranty difference between roof paint and roof restoration?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Manufacturer system warranties on roof coatings (Dulux Acratex, Astec, Nutech) require the substrate to be sound — that's a defined condition in the warranty terms. If the pointing fails after the paint goes on, the manufacturer warranty doesn't cover the resulting paint failure, because the cause sits below the coating. A roof paint alone might carry a 5-year workmanship warranty from the installer but the manufacturer system warranty isn't engaged. A full restoration with flexible pointing and replaced tiles gets you a manufacturer-backed 10-year system warranty on top of the workmanship warranty, because the substrate is now defined-sound. The dollar difference between the two jobs is mostly the difference between buying yourself five years and buying yourself fifteen." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Roof paint vs roof restoration in Hobart — different jobs"
  description="Why a re-coat without re-point is cosmetic on a Hobart tile roof. When a true restoration is mandatory, what a cheap roof-paint quote leaves out, and the system-warranty difference."
  canonical="https://hobarthousepainters.com.au/roof-paint-vs-restoration-hobart/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Tile roof &middot; bedding + pointing &middot; system warranty</span>
      <h1>Roof paint vs roof restoration in <span class="accent">Hobart</span> — different jobs.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        A roof paint and a roof restoration aren't two prices for the same job.
        They're two different jobs that look identical for the first six months.
        On a Hobart tile roof — most of the post-war housing stock through
        Glenorchy, Moonah, Lindisfarne and the eastern shore — the difference
        between them is whether you buy three years or fifteen. Here's how to
        tell what your roof actually needs.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/" aria-label="Call us"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a free quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>What each job actually involves.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">

        <h3>The roof paint — what's in the can and on the roof.</h3>
        <p>
          A roof paint is a three-stage cosmetic job. Stage one: high-pressure
          wash to remove mildew, moss and chalked-off pigment from the previous
          coat. Stage two: a primer sealer to bind down any remaining oxidised
          surface. Stage three: a two-coat acrylic membrane topcoat — usually
          Dulux Acratex, Astec or Nutech depending on the colour selection.
          That's the entire job. There's no structural work, no replacement,
          and no addressing of what's under the tiles.
        </p>
        <p>
          Done well, a roof paint will hold colour for 8-10 years on a sound
          Hobart tile roof. Done over failed pointing or broken tiles, the
          coating fails locally where water tracks through joints, and you see
          dark wet patches reappearing within two summers.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The roof restoration — structural plus cosmetic.</h3>
        <p>
          A full restoration adds three or four stages before the paint job
          even starts. First, full inspection of the ridge line and hip
          capping — every cap is checked for movement, every pointing run for
          cracking, every tile for hairline fracture. Second, broken tiles are
          replaced from salvage stock or matched-profile new stock. Third,
          loose ridge caps are re-bedded with a fresh mortar bed. Fourth, the
          entire ridge and hip pointing is removed and replaced with flexible
          pointing compound — a polymer-modified product that moves with the
          building rather than cracking when it gets cold. Only then does the
          wash-prime-coat sequence run.
        </p>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Why Hobart's climate makes the pointing question critical.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Hobart sits at the southernmost point of any mainland Australian
          city and gets a winter freeze-thaw cycle that Sydney and Brisbane
          don't. On a clear winter night with a sky-temperature reading well
          below ambient air, roof surface temperature can drop below zero
          even when air temperature is sitting at 3-4°C. That's normal for
          July and August across Hobart, the eastern shore and especially the
          higher suburbs — South Hobart, Mount Stuart, parts of West Hobart.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rigid mortar pointing — the traditional cement-sand-oxide mix that
          went on every Hobart tile roof built before 1990 — does not handle
          freeze-thaw. Each cycle of freezing water expanding inside hairline
          cracks slowly opens the cracks wider. Twenty cycles per winter, over
          thirty years, and the pointing is structurally finished. You can
          paint over the top of it and from ground level it looks beautiful.
          The next winter rain finds the cracks and the roof leaks at the
          ridge.
        </p>
        <p>
          Flexible pointing — a polymer-modified mortar — moves with the
          building and doesn't fatigue the same way. That's what every
          restoration we do uses. It's not optional on a Hobart roof.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>How to read the quote line items.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          The trap is the headline price. A "paint your roof from $2,800"
          quote in the local paper is essentially always paint-only —
          wash, prime, two coats, no structural work, no warranty engagement
          on the substrate. On a 1970s tile roof in Moonah where the pointing
          is at end-of-life, that's two summers of looking nice followed by
          leaks. Always check the line items.
        </p>
        <p>
          A genuine restoration quote will explicitly list: ridge cap
          inspection and re-bedding allowance, broken tile replacement
          allowance (usually a number-of-tiles count), flexible pointing
          run-metres (the total ridge and hip metres being re-pointed), and
          then the wash-prime-coat sequence. If those four line items aren't
          on the quote, it's a paint job dressed up as a restoration.
        </p>
        <p>
          One honest middle path: a hybrid quote where the painter inspects
          the roof, identifies the pointing as sound, prices the paint-only
          job, and explicitly states in writing that the pointing was assessed
          as sound on inspection. That's a valid paint-only quote on the
          right roof. The wrong roof is one where nobody actually inspected
          the pointing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>System warranty — the real number.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Manufacturer system warranties on roof coatings (Dulux Acratex,
          Astec, Nutech) are conditional on a defined-sound substrate. Read
          the warranty terms and you'll find a clause specifying that the
          underlying tile, bedding and pointing must be structurally sound
          at application. If they're not, and the coating fails because
          water came through a pointing joint, the manufacturer warranty
          doesn't cover the resulting paint failure. You'd be left with the
          installer's workmanship warranty — typically five years — and only
          for the application defects, not the underlying cause.
        </p>
        <p>
          A full restoration engages the manufacturer system warranty
          properly. With flexible pointing and replaced tiles, the substrate
          is now defined-sound, and you get the 10-year manufacturer system
          warranty on top of the installer's workmanship warranty. The dollar
          difference between paint-only and restoration on a typical Hobart
          tile roof is usually around 40-60% extra. The warranty difference
          is roughly three-times the protection. That's the real economics of
          the decision.
        </p>
        <p>
          We work to AS/NZS 2311 on the coating side and to the manufacturer
          system specification on the structural side, and we lodge the
          system warranty paperwork on every restoration so the homeowner
          has the document in hand at completion. Registered with Consumer
          Building and Occupational Services Tasmania, Master Painters
          Tasmania members.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Common questions about roof paint and restoration in Hobart.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">

        <h3>What's the difference between paint and restoration?</h3>
        <p>
          A roof paint is just the topcoat — clean, prime, coat. A roof
          restoration includes the structural work underneath: re-bedding
          loose ridge capping, re-pointing the ridge and hip line with
          flexible compound, replacing broken tiles, and only then doing
          wash-prime-coat. On Hobart tile roofs the bedding and pointing are
          usually the actual problem.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">How do I tell if I need a restoration?</h3>
        <p>
          Three checks: walk the perimeter and look for cracked or missing
          pointing on the ridge line; look for displaced or broken tiles in
          the field; get into the roof space on a wet day and look for
          active drips or water staining on rafters. One stain under the
          ridge is a definitive restoration call.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">What does a cheap roof-paint quote leave out?</h3>
        <p>
          Almost always the bedding and pointing inspection, the broken-tile
          replacement allowance, and the workmanship warranty on the
          structural elements. Hobart's freeze-thaw cycle accelerates rigid
          mortar pointing failure compared to mainland cities — always
          check the line items.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">What's the warranty difference?</h3>
        <p>
          Paint-only gets you the installer's workmanship warranty (typically
          5 years) but the manufacturer system warranty isn't engaged if the
          substrate isn't sound. A full restoration with flexible pointing
          gets you a manufacturer-backed 10-year system warranty plus
          workmanship — roughly three times the protection for around
          40-60% more upfront cost.
        </p>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner" style="text-align: center;">
      <h2>Want an honest read on your roof?</h2>
      <p style="max-width: 45rem; margin: 1rem auto;">
        We'll do a 32-point inspection at quote stage, get you onto the right
        path — paint or full restoration — and put the rationale in writing.
        Hobart-wide: Glenorchy, Moonah, Lindisfarne, Bellerive, Kingston, New
        Town. AS/NZS 2311 workmanship, manufacturer-backed system warranty.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content: center;">
        <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Email quotes@hobarthousepainters.com.au</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
